tr.th: Conclusion and Recommendations based on this report and previous findings known to us

tr.td: The patient shows elevated creatinine, significant proteinuria, glucosuria, and ketonuria, with low urine specific gravity and normal blood glucose. These findings suggest possible renal impairment (likely chronic kidney disease) and impaired tubular function. The presence of ketones and glucose in urine despite normal blood glucose and low HbA1c may indicate a non-diabetic cause, such as starvation or another metabolic disorder. Urine abnormalities (cloudy, brown, ammoniacal) further support renal pathology. Recommend nephrology evaluation and further workup.
